				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$HD\left( {f_{i}, f_{j} } \right)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M52"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>H</mml:mi><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2020_3775_Article_IEq23.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> equals zero, it can be concluded that these fragments are originated from the same chromosome copy, otherwise, the fragments belong to different chromosome copy, or some of their positions are destroyed by noise. To solve the problem, the fragments of the SNP matrix must be divided into two clusters such that the elements of each cluster will be compatible by the minimum number of letter flips i.e. MEC measure is minimized. Then, the center of each cluster equals with its corresponding haplotype. Figure <xref rid="Fig6" ref-type="fig">6</xref>, demonstrates the haplotype reconstruction in the diploid genome, <italic>X</italic> is SNP matrix which divided into two parts and <inline-formula id="IEq24"><alternatives><tex-math id="M53">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
